WEBVTT

00:01.835 --> 00:06.131
[metal clangs,
flames crackle]

00:06.131 --> 00:08.050
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:08.050 --> 00:11.720
<i>‐ Tonight, we embark on an</i>
<i>epic five‐week tournament:</i>

00:11.720 --> 00:13.430
our Battle of
the Branches competition.

00:13.430 --> 00:15.432
<i>Top bladesmiths</i>
<i>from four branches</i>

00:15.432 --> 00:17.184
<i>of our United States</i>
<i>Armed Forces:</i>

00:17.184 --> 00:20.479
<i>army, air force,</i>
<i>marine corps, and navy</i>

00:20.479 --> 00:22.898
<i>will put their blade‐making</i>
<i>skills to the test.</i>

00:22.898 --> 00:25.359
<i>The winner from each branch</i>
<i>will go head‐to‐head</i>

00:25.359 --> 00:26.985
<i>for our biggest</i>
<i>cash prize ever:</i>

00:26.985 --> 00:28.570
$50,000.

00:28.570 --> 00:29.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:29.738 --> 00:30.989
<i>Right now,</i>

00:30.989 --> 00:32.199
<i>round one belongs to the army.</i>

00:32.199 --> 00:34.117
‐ I love being
with my brothers.

00:34.117 --> 00:35.244
‐ There's gonna be
some bragging rights

00:35.244 --> 00:36.245
at the end of this deal.

00:36.245 --> 00:37.871
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:37.871 --> 00:39.540
<i>‐ Four soldiers must adapt</i>
<i>and overcome</i>

00:39.540 --> 00:40.958
<i>for a shot at representing</i>
<i>their branch</i>

00:40.958 --> 00:42.501
<i>in the first ever</i>

00:42.501 --> 00:44.503
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>Battle of the Branches.</i>

00:44.503 --> 00:47.214
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:47.214 --> 00:53.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:53.053 --> 00:55.097
<i>‐ My name is Fermin Lopez.</i>

00:55.097 --> 00:57.849
<i>I was a sergeant</i>
<i>in the United States Army.</i>

00:57.849 --> 00:59.768
I was a Black Hawk
combat medic.

00:59.768 --> 01:01.478
<i>We pretty much did</i>
<i>extractions,</i>

01:01.478 --> 01:03.063
<i>search and rescue.</i>

01:03.063 --> 01:04.523
<i>I can't wait to get out</i>
<i>on the floor,</i>

01:04.523 --> 01:05.899
play with the big toys.
I'm pumped up.

01:05.899 --> 01:07.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:07.609 --> 01:09.194
<i>‐ My name is Dave Fraughton,</i>
<i>34 years old.</i>

01:09.194 --> 01:11.405
I was a sniper in the army
for 12 years.

01:11.405 --> 01:14.283
<i>I've been forging</i>
<i>for six years now.</i>

01:14.283 --> 01:15.576
<i>It's great stress relief.</i>

01:15.576 --> 01:17.452
It's the only job
that you can have

01:17.452 --> 01:20.205
where you can fix your mistake
by beating it with a hammer.

01:20.205 --> 01:22.374
<i>‐ I'm Jack Stottlemire,</i>
<i>54 years old.</i>

01:22.374 --> 01:24.585
<i>I've been bladesmithing</i>
<i>for seven years now.</i>

01:24.585 --> 01:27.504
I'm a retired sergeant major.
United States Army.

01:27.504 --> 01:29.673
<i>I want to do a competition</i>
<i>to help promote</i>

01:29.673 --> 01:31.174
<i>the veteran charity work</i>
<i>that I do</i>

01:31.174 --> 01:34.595
to benefit
my fellow veterans.

01:34.595 --> 01:37.347
<i>‐ My name is Tyler Hackbarth,</i>
<i>I'm 32 years old,</i>

01:37.347 --> 01:40.058
and I was an E‐5 sergeant
for six years in the army.

01:40.058 --> 01:42.477
<i>I think fast, react quickly,</i>

01:42.477 --> 01:44.521
and my ability to do a lot
of different techniques,

01:44.521 --> 01:47.149
I think, is gonna give me
an edge above the other smiths.

01:47.149 --> 01:48.692
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:48.692 --> 01:50.569
‐ Soldiers, welcome
to The Forge.

01:50.569 --> 01:52.946
Today is unlike any other day
in The Forge because today,

01:52.946 --> 01:55.824
we kick off our Battle
of the Branches competition.

01:55.824 --> 01:57.784
This is where veterans
and members

01:57.784 --> 02:00.996
of the United States Marine
Corps, Navy, Air Force,

02:00.996 --> 02:02.789
and today, the Army,
compete for the title

02:02.789 --> 02:06.376
of "Forged in Fire" Champion
and for $50,000.

02:06.376 --> 02:09.880
This is your opportunity
to bring the title to the army,

02:09.880 --> 02:13.216
gents, all in front
of our panel of expert judges.

02:13.216 --> 02:16.386
Up first, ABS Mastersmith
J. Neilson.

02:16.386 --> 02:18.430
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

02:18.430 --> 02:20.057
David Baker,

02:20.057 --> 02:22.142
and last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

02:22.142 --> 02:24.061
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:24.061 --> 02:27.147
In The Forge today, soldiers,
you'll be making one of these.

02:27.147 --> 02:29.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:29.775 --> 02:32.944
<i>That's a V‐42 stiletto,</i>
<i>a dagger specifically designed</i>

02:32.944 --> 02:36.490
<i>for the army commandos of the</i>
<i>First Special Services Force</i>

02:36.490 --> 02:39.701
<i>for use during close‐quarters</i>
<i>combat during World War II.</i>

02:39.701 --> 02:42.204
<i>Your blades must be between</i>
<i>8 and 10 inches in length,</i>

02:42.204 --> 02:44.748
<i>include a through‐tang,</i>
<i>a 1‐inch ricasso,</i>

02:44.748 --> 02:47.793
and a textured thumb rest
on the ricasso.

02:47.793 --> 02:51.338
You have 10‐series steel
to use to forge these blades.

02:51.338 --> 02:53.090
<i>‐ Oh, my God.</i>

02:53.090 --> 02:55.592
<i>We have to re‐create</i>
<i>a double‐edged, quad,</i>

02:55.592 --> 02:56.885
<i>hollow‐grind knife.</i>

02:56.885 --> 02:59.596
This is gonna be
extremely difficult.

02:59.596 --> 03:01.723
‐ You'll have three hours
on the clock.

03:01.723 --> 03:03.684
In the second round,
you'll be attaching handles

03:03.684 --> 03:06.436
to these blades, turning them
into fully functional stilettos

03:06.436 --> 03:09.147
that will be tested
for strength and durability

03:09.147 --> 03:11.191
in an ammo‐can stab

03:11.191 --> 03:14.695
and for edge retention
in a parachute harness slice.

03:14.695 --> 03:16.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:16.154 --> 03:18.281
Good luck.
Your three hours starts now.

03:18.281 --> 03:20.909
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:20.909 --> 03:23.453
‐ We've got our four soldiers
all on a mission

03:23.453 --> 03:26.915
to re‐create
a V‐42 stiletto blade.

03:26.915 --> 03:30.419
These guys have a piece
of 10‐series monosteel.

03:30.419 --> 03:32.921
‐ It's a good, clean,
easy‐working steel.

03:32.921 --> 03:34.381
It's very forgiving.

03:34.381 --> 03:36.174
‐ Unlike normally,
when we had these guys

03:36.174 --> 03:38.343
salvage lawnmowers and bicycles
and all that stuff,

03:38.343 --> 03:39.970
we're giving them
straight steel

03:39.970 --> 03:42.389
because that dagger blade
is gonna be so difficult

03:42.389 --> 03:44.057
to forge,
heat‐treat and grind.

03:44.057 --> 03:46.184
‐ Go for it, buddy.
‐ It's very thin, very light.

03:46.184 --> 03:48.186
There's not a lot
of profile to it.

03:48.186 --> 03:50.730
So keeping that blade strong
is gonna be the trick.

03:50.730 --> 03:52.524
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:52.524 --> 03:54.943
‐ My strategy to get through
round one will be patience.

03:54.943 --> 03:56.403
Don't shut yours off!

03:56.403 --> 03:58.071
<i>The welder's not working,</i>

03:58.071 --> 04:00.740
<i>so I wait till</i>
<i>Tyler's finished with his.</i>

04:00.740 --> 04:03.201
‐ You're good, man.
<i>‐ I'm losing time,</i>

04:03.201 --> 04:05.036
but as a combat medic,

04:05.036 --> 04:07.789
you are trained to deal
with pretty much anything.

04:07.789 --> 04:09.958
‐ I like seeing Fermin marking
his measurements down

04:09.958 --> 04:11.126
while the steel's heating up.

04:11.126 --> 04:12.377
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:12.377 --> 04:13.420
‐ A lot of people go home

04:13.420 --> 04:15.172
because...the perimeters.

04:15.172 --> 04:16.590
<i>That's not happening to me.</i>

04:16.590 --> 04:20.135
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:20.135 --> 04:21.720
<i>‐ Making this dagger today</i>

04:21.720 --> 04:23.430
is actually a very,
very difficult thing to do

04:23.430 --> 04:25.390
'cause it's a quad
hollow grind.

04:25.390 --> 04:27.476
<i>Quad hollow grind is where</i>
<i>you have</i>

04:27.476 --> 04:29.728
<i>actually four surfaces</i>
<i>that have to be ground,</i>

04:29.728 --> 04:31.480
<i>and they all have to match.</i>

04:31.480 --> 04:33.064
<i>And to get</i>
<i>everything symmetrical</i>

04:33.064 --> 04:36.568
and everything straight
is a very difficult task.

04:36.568 --> 04:39.154
‐ It's a proven, strong way
to build a blade.

04:39.154 --> 04:41.072
You've got that high,
medial ridge

04:41.072 --> 04:43.575
running almost all the way
to the tip. Supports the blade.

04:43.575 --> 04:46.369
It gives you a really tight,
sharp edge.

04:46.369 --> 04:48.121
‐ My game plan is just to
stick to the basics.

04:48.121 --> 04:49.873
Nothing fancy.

04:49.873 --> 04:53.043
Make a functional weapon
that survives the testing.

04:53.043 --> 04:56.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:56.254 --> 04:58.882
‐ Dave, going right to
hand‐hammering on the anvil.

04:58.882 --> 04:59.925
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:59.925 --> 05:01.301
‐ I'd wanna reduce that

05:01.301 --> 05:02.886
either on the press
or on big blue

05:02.886 --> 05:04.429
before I started
swinging a hammer at it.

05:04.429 --> 05:05.972
‐ Yeah, that's for sure.

05:05.972 --> 05:08.058
<i>‐ My number one goal is I have</i>
<i>to take</i>

05:08.058 --> 05:11.728
this 1‐inch square stock
and make it flat.

05:11.728 --> 05:13.480
Holy [bleep].

05:13.480 --> 05:14.981
<i>I turn around,</i>

05:14.981 --> 05:17.901
and Jack has
four feet drawn out already.

05:17.901 --> 05:19.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:19.653 --> 05:21.696
Don't do it by hand.
‐ No, no. I don't have enough.

05:21.696 --> 05:23.824
[laughs]

05:23.824 --> 05:25.742
‐ Big blue it is.

05:25.742 --> 05:27.661
‐ That's what you gotta love
about the military.

05:27.661 --> 05:29.371
If you don't know
what you should be doing,

05:29.371 --> 05:31.164
look at the guy next to you.
Do what he's doing.

05:31.164 --> 05:32.374
‐ Yup.

05:32.374 --> 05:33.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:33.708 --> 05:35.293
<i>‐ My game plan right off</i>
<i>the top</i>

05:35.293 --> 05:37.504
is squashing that 1x1
piece of steel down.

05:37.504 --> 05:38.588
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:38.588 --> 05:40.507
<i>The power hammer is taken.</i>

05:40.507 --> 05:41.883
<i>When stuff happens</i>
<i>in the army,</i>

05:41.883 --> 05:43.718
you gotta act and not react.

05:43.718 --> 05:45.929
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:45.929 --> 05:47.556
‐ All right, another option:
straight to the press.

05:47.556 --> 05:49.349
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:49.349 --> 05:51.184
<i>‐ Even though I can't get on</i>
<i>the power hammer,</i>

05:51.184 --> 05:52.894
in the meantime, I'm making
that material move for me.

05:52.894 --> 05:54.145
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:54.145 --> 05:55.730
‐ One hour has elapsed!

05:55.730 --> 05:58.066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:58.066 --> 05:59.860
<i>‐ So I'm trying to get</i>
<i>everything as flat as I can,</i>

05:59.860 --> 06:01.862
so I can go ahead
and get a point on it‐‐make

06:01.862 --> 06:04.739
sure that it's nice and thin,
just like the blade.

06:04.739 --> 06:06.950
<i>We're all having fun.</i>
<i>We're brothers in arms.</i>

06:06.950 --> 06:08.451
There's nothing like it.

06:08.451 --> 06:09.953
<i>Once I have mine</i>
<i>pointing up too far,</i>

06:09.953 --> 06:11.705
<i>I take it</i>
<i>to do a thermal cycle.</i>

06:11.705 --> 06:13.999
<i>I think two cycles</i>
<i>should be enough.</i>

06:13.999 --> 06:15.750
<i>The reason why you</i>
<i>do thermal cycles</i>

06:15.750 --> 06:18.128
is because when you're given
a billet that is so thick,

06:18.128 --> 06:20.380
you're actually
pounding that metal together.

06:20.380 --> 06:22.591
<i>And in order for that metal</i>
<i>not to crack on you,</i>

06:22.591 --> 06:24.301
you have to do
some thermal cycles.

06:24.301 --> 06:26.511
That way, the metal can adjust
to the temperature.

06:26.511 --> 06:28.889
‐ How you doin', Fermin?
‐ Good, good. You?

06:28.889 --> 06:31.641
‐ With a thin blade like that,
it's all about thermal cycling

06:31.641 --> 06:33.476
the blade to make it stronger.

06:33.476 --> 06:36.563
‐ It's hot. [laughs]

06:36.563 --> 06:38.565
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:38.565 --> 06:41.276
‐ My strengths in bladesmithing
is I can hit steel really hard,

06:41.276 --> 06:43.987
<i>so shaping comes</i>
<i>pretty easy to me.</i>

06:43.987 --> 06:45.530
<i>I just want to make sure</i>
<i>that both sides</i>

06:45.530 --> 06:47.616
are equal and consistent
to each other.

06:47.616 --> 06:50.160
<i>Symmetry makes everything</i>
<i>in a stiletto.</i>

06:50.160 --> 06:53.496
I love being with my brothers.
This is awesome.

06:53.496 --> 06:55.624
I really wanna help
my fellow veterans.

06:55.624 --> 06:57.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:57.125 --> 06:58.627
<i>My charity is called</i>
<i>Conflict Forge.</i>

06:58.627 --> 07:00.629
I take steel
from our nation's battlefields

07:00.629 --> 07:03.340
from all over the world and
make functional art out of it.

07:03.340 --> 07:05.216
<i>And those go up for auction,</i>

07:05.216 --> 07:08.637
and 100% of the proceeds
benefit veteran charities.

07:08.637 --> 07:10.430
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:10.430 --> 07:13.016
‐ The importance of having
this blade perfectly true

07:13.016 --> 07:16.144
and straight is because
David Baker will find

07:16.144 --> 07:18.104
where and why it's crooked.

07:18.104 --> 07:20.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:20.231 --> 07:21.858
Yeah, buddy!

07:21.858 --> 07:23.109
The blade comes out straight,

07:23.109 --> 07:24.778
<i>I've got a tint put on,</i>

07:24.778 --> 07:28.198
<i>and just to make sure,</i>
<i>I measure it.</i>

07:28.198 --> 07:29.991
I made it too long!

07:29.991 --> 07:31.701
I'm almost an inch too long.

07:31.701 --> 07:34.954
I'm gonna cut off that tip
and reforge a new tip.

07:34.954 --> 07:36.539
‐ One of them's a sniper,
right?

07:36.539 --> 07:37.624
‐ Yeah.
‐ Uh, yeah.

07:37.624 --> 07:38.708
‐ Dave.

07:38.708 --> 07:40.710
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:40.710 --> 07:42.754
<i>‐ I was in</i>
<i>a mountain warfare unit,</i>

07:42.754 --> 07:45.215
and having done
all of that training

07:45.215 --> 07:47.008
and then going
to sniper school,

07:47.008 --> 07:49.594
<i>it's made living in</i>
<i>the mountains second nature.</i>

07:49.594 --> 07:52.472
I love hunting, so being
a sniper is kinda cheating.

07:52.472 --> 07:53.682
<i>[laughs]</i>

07:53.682 --> 07:55.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:55.392 --> 07:56.893
<i>‐ I'm starting to form my tip</i>

07:56.893 --> 07:58.603
<i>and get that drawn</i>
<i>on right now,</i>

07:58.603 --> 08:00.563
and then I'm gonna start
drawing out that through‐tang,

08:00.563 --> 08:02.399
and then work on
my blade shape from there.

08:02.399 --> 08:04.859
<i>It's very important to have</i>
<i>that tang straight</i>

08:04.859 --> 08:07.946
<i>and flat and center‐aligned</i>
<i>with the blade as well,</i>

08:07.946 --> 08:09.948
so that the weight and the feel
of everything in that blade

08:09.948 --> 08:11.783
is just flawless.

08:11.783 --> 08:13.910
Oh, Lord, that feels good.

08:13.910 --> 08:15.370
‐ [laughing] Yeah.

08:15.370 --> 08:18.331
‐ That's Dave. That's Tyler.

08:18.331 --> 08:19.999
They could be brothers,
those two.

08:19.999 --> 08:21.501
‐ They're pretty close, yeah.
‐ [laughs]

08:21.501 --> 08:22.794
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:22.794 --> 08:24.129
‐ The experience
in the army for me

08:24.129 --> 08:25.714
was great‐‐camaraderie,

08:25.714 --> 08:27.465
the brotherhood and everything.

08:27.465 --> 08:30.009
I let my hair down.
‐ Right?

08:30.009 --> 08:34.139
‐ It really formed the way
I operate in my life now.

08:34.139 --> 08:36.891
‐ Let's cuddle.
‐ How you doin'?

08:36.891 --> 08:38.601
‐ Wanna rub
our beards together?

08:38.601 --> 08:40.270
‐ [laughs]

08:40.270 --> 08:41.771
‐ Some people do find love
in "Forged in Fire."

08:41.771 --> 08:43.606
[laughter]

08:43.606 --> 08:45.525
‐ Two hours has elapsed!

08:45.525 --> 08:47.485
‐ You ever hollow grind before?
‐ Yeah.

08:47.485 --> 08:49.612
‐ I haven't. [laughs]
‐ No?

08:49.612 --> 08:52.490
‐ Belt grinding is one
of my things I enjoy.

08:52.490 --> 08:54.159
<i>I start my hollow grind</i>

08:54.159 --> 08:56.494
<i>from the ricasso</i>
<i>all the way to the tip.</i>

08:56.494 --> 08:58.580
‐ Well Fermin's throwing a lot
of sparks over there.

08:58.580 --> 09:00.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:00.457 --> 09:02.375
<i>‐ I'm comfortable with the way</i>
<i>the blade is looking,</i>

09:02.375 --> 09:05.587
so now my next step is to get
that thumb rest on the blade.

09:05.587 --> 09:08.173
‐ Now, that's a textured
thumb groove.

09:08.173 --> 09:09.883
How do you do that, J.?

09:09.883 --> 09:11.634
‐ Quickest way to do it
would be the rotary tool.

09:11.634 --> 09:13.887
‐ Okay
‐ You just dimple it in there.

09:13.887 --> 09:15.722
‐ Doesn't get any better
than that!

09:15.722 --> 09:17.057
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:17.057 --> 09:18.516
‐ I've got it profiled,

09:18.516 --> 09:20.518
I've got it to the thickness
I want it.

09:20.518 --> 09:23.104
I'm about ready to start
grinding my bevels now.

09:23.104 --> 09:24.606
On a piece like this,

09:24.606 --> 09:26.191
I will spend a lot of time
on the grinder.

09:26.191 --> 09:28.485
<i>I need to make</i>
<i>these hollow grinds</i>

09:28.485 --> 09:29.819
<i>perfect and symmetrical.</i>

09:29.819 --> 09:31.321
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:31.321 --> 09:33.573
‐ Jack just stripped off
that locking arm.

09:33.573 --> 09:35.533
‐ Yeah, Jack just
broke the grinder.

09:35.533 --> 09:37.202
<i>‐ Sometimes I can be a little</i>
<i>heavy‐handed.</i>

09:37.202 --> 09:38.828
<i>I'm a big guy</i>
<i>and stuff like that.</i>

09:38.828 --> 09:40.580
In Iraq and Afghanistan,
in my old unit,

09:40.580 --> 09:43.249
they used to have to
circle‐X "Jack" on everything

09:43.249 --> 09:44.959
'cause I would break [bleep]
all the time.

09:44.959 --> 09:47.128
‐ Now Jack, heading over
to the grinder

09:47.128 --> 09:48.671
on the left side of The Forge

09:48.671 --> 09:51.925
after just manhandling
this grinder closest to us.

09:51.925 --> 09:53.843
‐ I don't think I'm gonna
invite Jack to my shop.

09:53.843 --> 09:55.428
‐ [laughs]

09:55.428 --> 09:57.055
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:57.055 --> 09:59.349
‐ I'm gonna make it look good
for the ladies.

09:59.349 --> 10:00.767
<i>I got all the forging done.</i>

10:00.767 --> 10:02.435
<i>This knife needs</i>
<i>hollow grinds,</i>

10:02.435 --> 10:06.439
and I've never used
a belt grinder before.

10:06.439 --> 10:08.066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:08.066 --> 10:09.984
<i>Back in my shop,</i>
<i>I just use an angle grinder.</i>

10:09.984 --> 10:13.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:13.154 --> 10:15.281
‐ You need to have support
on both sides of it,

10:15.281 --> 10:18.159
'cause you can see where Dave's
on one side of it

10:18.159 --> 10:19.702
and the blade's
jumping all over the place.

10:19.702 --> 10:20.995
‐ Right.
‐ You're not gonna get smooth,

10:20.995 --> 10:22.664
even grinds that way.

10:22.664 --> 10:24.999
<i>‐ If you look at</i>
<i>that belt grinder</i>

10:24.999 --> 10:26.626
<i>with sparks flying everywhere</i>

10:26.626 --> 10:29.003
<i>and you're about to go</i>
<i>put your fingers</i>

10:29.003 --> 10:31.464
a sixteenth of an inch away
from it...

10:31.464 --> 10:33.007
there's a little
bit of trepidation.

10:33.007 --> 10:36.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:36.302 --> 10:38.805
‐ Bladesmiths, there are only
30 minutes remaining

10:38.805 --> 10:40.014
in this round.

10:40.014 --> 10:42.809
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:42.809 --> 10:44.686
I hope those
are lucky lips, baby.

10:44.686 --> 10:47.313
‐ [laughs]

10:47.313 --> 10:49.440
Before I get into the quench,
I'm looking at my blade

10:49.440 --> 10:51.234
to make sure that
I'm not overheating it,

10:51.234 --> 10:54.445
make sure that it's got
a very nice golden color on it.

10:54.445 --> 10:56.364
I can see better now.
‐ [laughs]

10:56.364 --> 11:00.618
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:00.618 --> 11:02.704
‐ All right, so Fermin
has just quenched.

11:02.704 --> 11:05.498
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:05.498 --> 11:07.250
Looks pretty straight to me.

11:07.250 --> 11:11.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:11.629 --> 11:13.339
‐ Oh, yeah, it's hard. Yeah.

11:13.339 --> 11:15.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:15.466 --> 11:16.885
‐ What Jack's
doing is smart‐‐

11:16.885 --> 11:18.511
heating up the base
of the blade,

11:18.511 --> 11:20.513
where the ricasso
is the thickest point.

11:20.513 --> 11:23.725
And using that rosebud torch
can actually keep the heat

11:23.725 --> 11:26.519
from traveling all the way
to the tip and overheating.

11:26.519 --> 11:28.855
<i>‐ The tip on this stiletto</i>
<i>is very, very fine.</i>

11:28.855 --> 11:31.482
It's almost needlelike,
and it's very easy

11:31.482 --> 11:33.443
<i>to harden the end of</i>
<i>your knife off in the forge.</i>

11:33.443 --> 11:35.195
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:35.195 --> 11:37.197
‐ Jack finally went in the oil.
‐ Finally quenched.

11:37.197 --> 11:38.656
‐ All right. What do we got?

11:38.656 --> 11:40.116
What do we got
comin' out of there?

11:40.116 --> 11:41.367
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:41.367 --> 11:43.786
‐ Ahh!
‐ Warped.

11:43.786 --> 11:46.164
‐ We got a problem
over here, gentlemen.

11:46.164 --> 11:48.208
‐ This warp could
send me home today,

11:48.208 --> 11:49.542
<i>so I have to get this out.</i>

11:49.542 --> 11:50.752
♪ ♪

11:50.752 --> 11:51.544
‐ Oh, be careful.

11:53.588 --> 11:58.092
‐ That's a b
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:58.092 --> 11:59.802
Nice.
‐ It looks nice.

11:59.802 --> 12:01.221
<i>‐ Warp's gone.</i>

12:01.221 --> 12:03.848
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:03.848 --> 12:05.892
‐ I'm a little worried about
the quench, uh, right now,

12:05.892 --> 12:09.312
because if this wants to warp,
as skinny as it is,

12:09.312 --> 12:11.147
it's gonna go pretty far.

12:11.147 --> 12:14.192
I'm hoping to see that
the blade comes out straight,

12:14.192 --> 12:18.196
<i>there's no crazy twists,</i>
<i>warps, corkscrews.</i>

12:18.196 --> 12:20.198
And all of those
things can go wrong.

12:20.198 --> 12:21.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:21.991 --> 12:24.118
‐ All right, so we're getting
a little bit of thermal cycling

12:24.118 --> 12:25.995
out of Dave.

12:25.995 --> 12:27.580
<i>‐ I pulled it out of</i>
<i>the forge‐‐it's really hot.</i>

12:27.580 --> 12:29.958
It only needs to be
slightly above magnetic,

12:29.958 --> 12:32.085
and I'm at a welding heat now.

12:32.085 --> 12:34.128
<i>So I need to let it cool down</i>
<i>just a little bit</i>

12:34.128 --> 12:35.755
<i>before I get it in the oil.</i>

12:35.755 --> 12:37.257
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:37.257 --> 12:38.841
‐ Oh, no.

12:38.841 --> 12:41.261
Dave's in the quench!
‐ Yep.

12:41.261 --> 12:43.763
‐ That was not a thermal cycle.
That blade looked hot.

12:43.763 --> 12:45.265
‐ And that's a recipe
for stress fractures

12:45.265 --> 12:47.267
and a brittle blade.
‐ Yep.

12:47.267 --> 12:51.437
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:51.437 --> 12:53.106
‐ Tyler's in the oil.
‐ Yep.

12:53.106 --> 12:54.774
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:54.774 --> 12:56.943
‐ I'm ecstatic with how it
comes out of the quench.

12:56.943 --> 12:58.528
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:58.528 --> 13:00.863
It's nice and straight.
I don't see any warps...

13:00.863 --> 13:02.156
<i>so I'm gonna proceed</i>
<i>to the thumbprint.</i>

13:02.156 --> 13:03.783
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:03.783 --> 13:04.993
<i>The army definitely</i>
<i>has a great chance</i>

13:04.993 --> 13:06.661
<i>of winning this whole thing.</i>

13:06.661 --> 13:08.371
The marines, unless they're
told to think something,

13:08.371 --> 13:10.456
they're not really gonna be
thinking it correctly,

13:10.456 --> 13:12.792
and then the navy‐‐if we put
enough water around them,

13:12.792 --> 13:14.961
they might be comfortable
and have a chance.

13:14.961 --> 13:17.171
In the air force, I didn't see
any chairs out there,

13:17.171 --> 13:20.633
so the chair force is probably
gonna be out of their element.

13:20.633 --> 13:25.346
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

13:25.346 --> 13:28.141
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines, drop your tools.

13:28.141 --> 13:30.560
This first round
of competition is over.

13:30.560 --> 13:31.978
‐ Whoo!
‐ Whoo!

13:31.978 --> 13:33.771
[applause]

13:33.771 --> 13:34.856
‐ Yeah!
‐ Good job.

13:34.856 --> 13:36.482
‐ Ooh, yeah.
‐ Yeah!

13:36.482 --> 13:38.234
<i>‐ I'm standing there</i>
<i>and I'm looking at</i>

13:38.234 --> 13:39.861
the other blades around me
from the other smiths,

13:39.861 --> 13:41.154
and I'm like "holy crap."

13:41.154 --> 13:42.238
It's anybody's game right now.

13:42.238 --> 13:43.948
Everybody did a fantastic job.

13:43.948 --> 13:46.492
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:46.492 --> 13:48.870
‐ All right bladesmiths,
the first round's over

13:48.870 --> 13:50.997
and it's time for the judges
to take a closer look

13:50.997 --> 13:53.166
at your work.
Tyler, you're up first.

13:53.166 --> 13:54.959
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:54.959 --> 13:57.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:57.670 --> 13:59.297
<i>‐ It's really nice work,</i>
<i>Tyler.</i>

13:59.297 --> 14:01.299
<i>You did a good job</i>
<i>drawing this out.</i>

14:01.299 --> 14:04.177
I like your little thumb index.
Your blade looks even,

14:04.177 --> 14:07.680
but I'd really rather have seen
some radius down in here

14:07.680 --> 14:09.515
instead of straight corners,

14:09.515 --> 14:11.392
'cause you got the possibility
of stress fractures.

14:11.392 --> 14:12.685
That's something
you could fix

14:12.685 --> 14:13.811
if you moved into
the next round.

14:13.811 --> 14:15.188
Nice job.
‐ Thank you

14:15.188 --> 14:16.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:16.564 --> 14:18.024
‐ Jack, if you win this
competition,

14:18.024 --> 14:19.901
you owe us a grinder.
But at this time,

14:19.901 --> 14:21.694
please present
your work to the judges.

14:21.694 --> 14:24.530
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:24.530 --> 14:26.866
‐ Just feels like you wanna
stick someone with it.

14:26.866 --> 14:29.035
‐ [chuckling]
‐ The grinds that you put

14:29.035 --> 14:31.204
on this are really beautiful.

14:31.204 --> 14:34.665
I like the fact that you got
this blade as lean as you did.

14:34.665 --> 14:37.627
You know, the symmetry
of your blade looks fantastic.

14:37.627 --> 14:38.711
It's really well done.

14:38.711 --> 14:40.046
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:40.046 --> 14:41.464
‐ All right Fermin, you're up.

14:41.464 --> 14:43.508
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:43.508 --> 14:45.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:45.885 --> 14:49.263
‐ It's light, it feels like
it'll move really well.

14:49.263 --> 14:51.015
Steel looks solid.

14:51.015 --> 14:54.602
I do notice that you ground
a bunch off one side,

14:54.602 --> 14:56.395
and then it gets fat
on this side,

14:56.395 --> 14:58.397
and then it gets fat
on this side.

14:58.397 --> 15:01.818
So, evening that grind out on a
thin blade like this is tough,

15:01.818 --> 15:03.402
but it's doable.

15:03.402 --> 15:05.321
‐ But also be very careful,

15:05.321 --> 15:07.490
because we're talking
about thrusting something

15:07.490 --> 15:09.492
and you need a solid foundation

15:09.492 --> 15:12.745
to be able to support the tip
as you're thrusting or slicing.

15:12.745 --> 15:14.455
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:14.455 --> 15:15.915
‐ Dave, you're up.

15:15.915 --> 15:17.125
Please present
your blade to the judges.

15:17.125 --> 15:19.127
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:19.127 --> 15:20.920
<i>‐ I like the shape,</i>
<i>it's a dagger style.</i>

15:20.920 --> 15:26.259
Definitely feels like...it's
ready to go kill. Good job.

15:26.259 --> 15:30.680
‐ Yeah, but you got a brown
crease going across the blade,

15:30.680 --> 15:32.765
<i>and it goes to</i>
<i>the other side also.</i>

15:32.765 --> 15:34.475
So, you've got a crack
in there.

15:34.475 --> 15:36.310
That's probably because
of how hot your blade was

15:36.310 --> 15:37.895
when you quenched it.

15:37.895 --> 15:39.730
It's nothing I can get
my fingernail into,

15:39.730 --> 15:41.607
so it's a stress fracture,

15:41.607 --> 15:43.151
but it runs halfway
through your blade.

15:43.151 --> 15:45.069
That's an issue.

15:45.069 --> 15:46.362
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:46.362 --> 15:47.989
‐ Bladesmiths, the
judges have made

15:47.989 --> 15:49.740
their final decision.

15:49.740 --> 15:52.118
It's time for one of you
bladesmiths to leave The Forge.

15:52.118 --> 15:53.995
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge...

15:53.995 --> 15:57.123
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:57.123 --> 15:58.291
Is Dave.

15:58.291 --> 16:00.042
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:00.042 --> 16:01.169
‐ Now Dave, first of all I want

16:01.169 --> 16:02.503
to thank you for your service,

16:02.503 --> 16:03.713
and we also appreciate the work

16:03.713 --> 16:05.506
you did here in this challenge.

16:05.506 --> 16:08.009
But at the end of the day,
having those stress fractures

16:08.009 --> 16:10.469
in several spots‐‐that's
why we're gonna let you go.

16:10.469 --> 16:12.013
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:12.013 --> 16:13.598
‐ Dave, please
surrender your blade.

16:13.598 --> 16:17.518
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:17.518 --> 16:19.270
‐ Thank you for your service.

16:19.270 --> 16:21.105
‐ Absolutely. Thanks.
‐ Thank you for your service.

16:21.105 --> 16:22.732
‐ Today was just a bad one.

16:22.732 --> 16:24.567
<i>I've definitely made</i>
<i>three new friends,</i>

16:24.567 --> 16:27.987
<i>and as long as the army wins,</i>
<i>that's all that matters.</i>

16:27.987 --> 16:29.238
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:29.238 --> 16:30.615
Keep it up, boys.

16:30.615 --> 16:34.076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:34.076 --> 16:35.912
‐ Congratulations bladesmiths,

16:35.912 --> 16:38.623
you've made it into the second
round of this competition.

16:38.623 --> 16:40.333
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

16:40.333 --> 16:42.418
it's time to turn them
into fully functional V‐42

16:42.418 --> 16:44.962
fighting knives
by attaching handles to them.

16:44.962 --> 16:47.048
<i>And the standard, of course,</i>
<i>is that you include</i>

16:47.048 --> 16:49.217
<i>a crossguard,</i>
<i>a stacked leather handle,</i>

16:49.217 --> 16:52.303
<i>and a skull cracker pommel</i>
<i>on the back of those blades</i>

16:52.303 --> 16:54.931
so that we can test them
for strength and durability

16:54.931 --> 16:56.182
in an ammo‐can stab...

16:56.182 --> 16:57.266
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:57.266 --> 16:58.559
And for edge retention

16:58.559 --> 17:00.353
in a parachute‐harness slice.

17:00.353 --> 17:01.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:01.854 --> 17:03.231
You only have two hours

17:03.231 --> 17:05.316
in which to complete
all of your work.

17:05.316 --> 17:06.901
I remind you that
after the test,

17:06.901 --> 17:08.569
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

17:08.569 --> 17:10.071
and leave The Forge.

17:10.071 --> 17:12.698
Good luck,
your two hours starts now.

17:12.698 --> 17:13.699
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:13.699 --> 17:15.034
These guys have two hours

17:15.034 --> 17:17.119
to make symmetrical
crossguards,

17:17.119 --> 17:20.081
stacked leather handles,
and a skull crusher pommel.

17:20.081 --> 17:22.750
‐ It's definitely a lot
to get done in two hours.

17:22.750 --> 17:24.377
‐ Doug, do you think
you could get

17:24.377 --> 17:26.796
a stacked leather handle
on these blades in two hours?

17:26.796 --> 17:29.423
‐ Of course!
[laughter]

17:29.423 --> 17:31.092
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:31.092 --> 17:32.885
<i>‐ Going into round two,</i>
<i>I grab the leather,</i>

17:32.885 --> 17:34.804
because that's the one thing
that's going to take time

17:34.804 --> 17:36.180
to get together.

17:36.180 --> 17:37.765
‐ I know doing the stacked
leather

17:37.765 --> 17:39.350
can get
kind of frustrating,

17:39.350 --> 17:41.102
especially with that clock
going on up there,

17:41.102 --> 17:43.271
so hopefully nobody shorts out
on the handle.

17:43.271 --> 17:45.856
<i>‐ I go ahead and I cut pieces</i>
<i>of leather</i>

17:45.856 --> 17:47.733
<i>and I set that aside.</i>

17:47.733 --> 17:49.569
For the guard,
I'm just gonna use mild steel.

17:49.569 --> 17:51.445
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:51.445 --> 17:53.406
<i>I made three holes,</i>
<i>which is a lot easier to file.</i>

17:53.406 --> 17:54.782
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:54.782 --> 17:56.075
<i>This is the harder part,</i>

17:56.075 --> 17:57.994
because you want to have
a nice flush

17:57.994 --> 17:59.328
that's not gonna twist on you.

17:59.328 --> 18:01.080
Sweet! Yes.

18:01.080 --> 18:02.999
<i>I do have full confidence</i>

18:02.999 --> 18:04.417
that my blade
is gonna perform well.

18:04.417 --> 18:07.837
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:07.837 --> 18:09.422
‐ Starting round two,

18:09.422 --> 18:11.173
I've got a lot of work
ahead of me right now.

18:11.173 --> 18:14.135
<i>I need to shave my tang,</i>
<i>get that rounded off</i>

18:14.135 --> 18:15.803
<i>so that I don't have</i>
<i>sharp corners in there</i>

18:15.803 --> 18:18.306
that could make a possible
weak point in my handle.

18:18.306 --> 18:20.516
<i>And then from there,</i>
<i>I'll get my die set up,</i>

18:20.516 --> 18:23.436
get some cutting oil on it,
and start threading it.

18:23.436 --> 18:26.480
<i>I'm running this die</i>
<i>over the end of the handle</i>

18:26.480 --> 18:27.940
to get threads on it,

18:27.940 --> 18:30.568
so then I can drill
and tap my pommel

18:30.568 --> 18:32.778
that'll screw on there
and hold everything together.

18:32.778 --> 18:34.530
At this point in time,
I'm pretty confident,

18:34.530 --> 18:36.115
but who knows
what kind of curveballs

18:36.115 --> 18:37.283
I'm gonna run into.

18:37.283 --> 18:39.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:39.744 --> 18:41.203
<i>‐ The bar stock,</i>
<i>it's so thick,</i>

18:41.203 --> 18:42.496
<i>I've gotta thin my steel out.</i>

18:42.496 --> 18:44.373
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:44.373 --> 18:46.584
‐ Jack is over here.
He's fitting up his guard.

18:46.584 --> 18:48.127
He's done a lot of work
with that,

18:48.127 --> 18:49.754
just kind of making sure
everything's perfect.

18:49.754 --> 18:51.380
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:51.380 --> 18:52.798
<i>‐ I get a hole drilled</i>
<i>through it</i>

18:52.798 --> 18:54.300
and I go to start filing it in,

18:54.300 --> 18:57.011
and I'm having issues
with the files.

18:57.011 --> 18:58.596
[bleep], this ain't gonna work.

18:58.596 --> 19:00.306
I can't find the right size
I'm looking for.

19:00.306 --> 19:02.975
<i>A lot of time</i>
<i>being wasted on this guard.</i>

19:02.975 --> 19:04.435
‐ One hour has elapsed!

19:04.435 --> 19:06.312
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:06.312 --> 19:08.898
‐ For the pommel, I'm using
brass. Then, my next step

19:08.898 --> 19:11.150
is to put all
the leather stacks together.

19:11.150 --> 19:13.194
‐ Fermin's going with the idea
of just punching one large,

19:13.194 --> 19:14.945
round hole

19:14.945 --> 19:16.572
in the middle of each
of those stacks of leather.

19:16.572 --> 19:18.491
So, that's gonna allow
that leather to spin

19:18.491 --> 19:20.826
if that glue doesn't
hold up or anything else.

19:20.826 --> 19:22.495
<i>‐ Once it's dry, I can go</i>
<i>ahead and give it</i>

19:22.495 --> 19:24.163
<i>a nice shape,</i>
<i>and then work on my blade.</i>

19:24.163 --> 19:26.165
'Cause this is what takes
the most time.

19:26.165 --> 19:27.750
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:27.750 --> 19:29.335
<i>‐ I've drilled the holes</i>
<i>in the guard,</i>

19:29.335 --> 19:31.337
started filing through
to get my slot opened up

19:31.337 --> 19:33.381
<i>and realize</i>
<i>it's not even close.</i>

19:33.381 --> 19:37.009
<i>My tang is thicker at the end</i>
<i>where the threads are</i>

19:37.009 --> 19:39.553
<i>than it is at that back</i>
<i>of the ricasso on my knife.</i>

19:39.553 --> 19:41.389
Gotta open up a hole
in the center of my guard

19:41.389 --> 19:43.057
for my threads
to slide through.

19:43.057 --> 19:44.850
We're close.

19:44.850 --> 19:46.602
<i>I'm also gonna have to go</i>
<i>back to the grinder</i>

19:46.602 --> 19:48.354
<i>and take some width</i>
<i>out of my tang.</i>

19:48.354 --> 19:50.398
The more time I take off
the clock with this,

19:50.398 --> 19:52.692
<i>the less time I've got to get</i>
<i>my leather punched and stacked</i>

19:52.692 --> 19:55.194
<i>and glued and finish</i>
<i>this blade for the judges.</i>

19:55.194 --> 19:56.946
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:56.946 --> 19:59.865
‐ Got my guard, my leather,
my pommel all glued in.

19:59.865 --> 20:01.534
After this is dried,

20:01.534 --> 20:04.161
then I'm gonna grind all this
off and shape my handle.

20:04.161 --> 20:06.330
<i>And then I'm going to drill</i>
<i>and pin my pommel.</i>

20:06.330 --> 20:07.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:07.540 --> 20:08.708
<i>For my pommel, I'm just gonna</i>

20:08.708 --> 20:10.084
drill a hole through there,

20:10.084 --> 20:12.128
<i>it's gonna fit inside,</i>

20:12.128 --> 20:14.004
<i>then I'm gonna cross‐drill it</i>
<i>through the tang and pin it.</i>

20:14.004 --> 20:15.923
That's the way
the original V‐42 was made.

20:15.923 --> 20:17.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:17.466 --> 20:19.009
<i>I'm using a carbide bit,</i>

20:19.009 --> 20:20.553
and carbide bits
are very short.

20:20.553 --> 20:22.221
<i>They don't go</i>
<i>all the way through.</i>

20:22.221 --> 20:26.016
‐ So, here we have Jack trying
to drill through his pommel.

20:26.016 --> 20:29.311
‐ Oh, no. I think Jack
drilled his pommel‐‐

20:29.311 --> 20:31.063
didn't drill
through his tang yet.

20:31.063 --> 20:32.815
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:32.815 --> 20:34.859
So, that tang's hard, and as
that drill bit's spinning,

20:34.859 --> 20:36.777
causing friction,
it's causing heat,

20:36.777 --> 20:39.238
and if that snaps in that hole,
that's gonna be a nightmare.

20:39.238 --> 20:40.614
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:40.614 --> 20:42.783
‐ Oh!
‐ Ohh. And there it happened.

20:42.783 --> 20:45.244
‐ Broken bit.
‐ Oh, shnikeys.

20:45.244 --> 20:46.454
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:46.454 --> 20:47.913
<i>‐ The drill bit snaps</i>

20:47.913 --> 20:50.040
‐‐breaks off into the pommel
and in my guard.

20:50.040 --> 20:51.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:51.500 --> 20:53.586
And I've got minutes
left on the clock.

20:53.586 --> 20:56.172
<i>Gotta get it out of there</i>
<i>and get my pin in.</i>

20:56.172 --> 20:57.840
‐ Jack is in a lot of trouble
right now.

20:57.840 --> 21:00.301
‐ Yeah. He needs a pin
inside that handle

21:00.301 --> 21:02.511
to get a solid
mechanical connection,

21:02.511 --> 21:03.929
and now he's got the drill
bit stuck inside there.

21:03.929 --> 21:04.722
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:08.517 --> 21:10.770
<i>‐ I was able to get</i>
<i>the drill bit out,</i>

21:10.770 --> 21:12.354
<i>and I'm mixing up my epoxy.</i>

21:12.354 --> 21:14.648
I get my pin coated
and I stick it in there.

21:14.648 --> 21:16.609
<i>I run over to the grinder</i>
<i>and I grind it off.</i>

21:16.609 --> 21:18.611
<i>But right now,</i>
<i>I don't know if that pin</i>

21:18.611 --> 21:20.237
is gonna hold
that pommel on or not.

21:20.237 --> 21:21.655
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:21.655 --> 21:23.491
‐ 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

21:23.491 --> 21:25.451
<i>‐ All that's left to do</i>

21:25.451 --> 21:27.953
<i>is address some of the flaws</i>
<i>that the judges mentioned.</i>

21:27.953 --> 21:29.789
My grind lines
were just a bit off,

21:29.789 --> 21:32.583
so by rearranging
my hollow grinds,

21:32.583 --> 21:34.210
it will make them straight.

21:34.210 --> 21:35.753
It's straight.

21:35.753 --> 21:37.171
Now, it's time
to sharpen the blade.

21:37.171 --> 21:38.881
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:38.881 --> 21:40.758
‐ I've never done a stacked
leather handle before.

21:40.758 --> 21:42.426
I'm just trying to do my best
to keep up with the clock.

21:42.426 --> 21:45.387
‐ Tyler's gonna drill through
all of his stacked

21:45.387 --> 21:46.764
leather at the same time.

21:46.764 --> 21:49.058
‐ So what do we expect
to see here?

21:49.058 --> 21:50.601
‐ Pfft. Leather confetti.

21:50.601 --> 21:52.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:52.978 --> 21:54.271
‐ It's working.

21:54.271 --> 21:56.315
‐ Yeah, it's going through.

21:56.315 --> 21:57.983
<i>‐ I really need to get</i>
<i>this handle put together</i>

21:57.983 --> 21:59.652
so it fits great
in the judges' hands,

21:59.652 --> 22:01.779
<i>but there's</i>
<i>no time left on the clock.</i>

22:01.779 --> 22:03.823
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:03.823 --> 22:06.992
‐ Clock's ticking down.
I got a couple minutes left

22:06.992 --> 22:09.078
<i>and I notice there's a gap</i>
<i>between the guard</i>

22:09.078 --> 22:11.497
and the ricasso,
and it's horrible.

22:11.497 --> 22:13.332
<i>So, I cut a piece</i>
<i>of leather out</i>

22:13.332 --> 22:16.335
<i>that matches the shape</i>
<i>of the guard and epoxy that</i>

22:16.335 --> 22:18.128
<i>and fit it on there</i>
<i>and that fills the gap.</i>

22:18.128 --> 22:20.673
That gap is another issue
that could send me home today.

22:20.673 --> 22:21.841
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:21.841 --> 22:24.468
‐ Ten, nine, eight,

22:24.468 --> 22:26.428
seven, six,

22:26.428 --> 22:29.139
five, four, three,

22:29.139 --> 22:31.475
two, one.

22:31.475 --> 22:33.185
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

22:33.185 --> 22:35.688
This second round
of competition is over.

22:35.688 --> 22:38.482
[applause]

22:38.482 --> 22:40.025
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:40.025 --> 22:42.695
‐ Round two was by far
the most stressful round.

22:42.695 --> 22:44.697
<i>I'm looking at Tyler's</i>
<i>and Fermin's blades</i>

22:44.697 --> 22:46.699
<i>and they made</i>
<i>outstanding weapons.</i>

22:46.699 --> 22:48.325
I'm hoping mine holds together

22:48.325 --> 22:50.327
and performs as well
as I think theirs will.

22:50.327 --> 22:54.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:54.206 --> 22:56.375
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to our strength test.

22:56.375 --> 22:58.043
The weapon you made
was required to have a strong,

22:58.043 --> 23:00.504
penetrating tip
and a skull cracker.

23:00.504 --> 23:02.214
Well, we're gonna put both
of those to the test

23:02.214 --> 23:04.717
in this ammo‐can stab and bash.

23:04.717 --> 23:07.553
Not really concerned about what
your blades do to the cans.

23:07.553 --> 23:09.889
I wanna see what the cans do
to your blades.

23:09.889 --> 23:12.474
Fermin, you're in first.
How do you feel?

23:12.474 --> 23:13.851
‐ Blood pressure high.
‐ That's all right,

23:13.851 --> 23:15.227
they have medication for that.

23:15.227 --> 23:17.563
‐ Yes, I am on it.
[laughter]

23:17.563 --> 23:20.065
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:20.065 --> 23:22.026
<i>If anything goes wrong</i>
<i>with my blade,</i>

23:22.026 --> 23:24.069
<i>it might be the point,</i>
<i>because you're stabbing metal.</i>

23:24.069 --> 23:26.530
And knowing J. Neilson,
he's gonna give it his all.

23:26.530 --> 23:28.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:28.240 --> 23:29.533
‐ [grunting]

23:29.533 --> 23:36.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:56.810 --> 24:00.606
All right, Fermin.
First off, the skull cracker.

24:00.606 --> 24:02.900
There's nothing here
to stop my hand from moving,

24:02.900 --> 24:04.944
so every time I would strike,

24:04.944 --> 24:06.654
it would go all the way
down to the can,

24:06.654 --> 24:09.740
so I could feel striking the
can with the back of my hand.

24:09.740 --> 24:13.869
Your blade held up, though.
You lost the very tip,

24:13.869 --> 24:15.746
and because you had
that thin spot,

24:15.746 --> 24:20.417
here‐‐thicker steel here‐‐and
it wasn't fully corrected,

24:20.417 --> 24:21.961
it's got a flex in the blade.

24:21.961 --> 24:24.129
But, otherwise, you survived.
Good job.

24:24.129 --> 24:26.882
‐ Thank you, sir.
‐ How you feeling, Jack?

24:26.882 --> 24:28.592
‐ Good.
‐ Good? I know you were

24:28.592 --> 24:30.803
looking forward to this.
‐ Oh, yeah. Yeah, absolutely.

24:30.803 --> 24:32.096
‐ All right, let's do it then.

24:32.096 --> 24:34.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:34.473 --> 24:36.600
<i>‐ Seeing what Fermin's blade</i>
<i>just went through,</i>

24:36.600 --> 24:37.977
<i>I hope my blade holds up,</i>

24:37.977 --> 24:40.020
but I don't know about
that damn pommel.

24:40.020 --> 24:43.315
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:43.315 --> 24:45.734
‐ [grunting]

24:48.946 --> 24:55.953
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:55.953 --> 24:59.164
[grunting]

25:05.671 --> 25:07.589
All right, Jack, first of all.

25:07.589 --> 25:09.842
The point in the skull cracker
and the rib around it

25:09.842 --> 25:11.844
made it nice penetrating.

25:11.844 --> 25:13.846
I put the three good
dimples in that can

25:13.846 --> 25:15.514
without any trouble at all.

25:15.514 --> 25:17.683
No movement on my hand
sliding back and forth.

25:17.683 --> 25:20.853
Your blade held up beautifully,
edge is great,

25:20.853 --> 25:23.480
you got your whole tip,
but your pommel's loosened up.

25:23.480 --> 25:24.815
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:24.815 --> 25:26.358
‐ [sighs]

25:26.358 --> 25:27.776
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:27.776 --> 25:29.319
‐ Apparently that pin
came all the way out.

25:29.319 --> 25:30.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:30.696 --> 25:32.031
I saw that you had
a pin going in,

25:32.031 --> 25:33.532
but it didn't go
all the way through,

25:33.532 --> 25:36.035
so it wasn't enough
to lock everything together.

25:36.035 --> 25:38.871
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:38.871 --> 25:41.331
‐ All right, Jack, you've got
a critical failure

25:41.331 --> 25:44.585
in your weapon system‐‐your
skull cracker's fallen off.

25:44.585 --> 25:47.212
Now, it would seem that
your fate lies in the hands

25:47.212 --> 25:50.049
and the strength and integrity
of Tyler's blade.

25:50.049 --> 25:52.009
Tyler, you're up next.

25:52.009 --> 25:54.219
If you pass this test,
you'll be moving on,

25:54.219 --> 25:56.555
and Jack, you'll be dismissed
from The Forge.

25:56.555 --> 25:58.015
Let's see what happens.

25:58.015 --> 26:00.059
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:00.059 --> 26:01.894
‐ All right, Tyler.
Are you ready?

26:01.894 --> 26:03.395
‐ Ready as I'll ever be.

26:03.395 --> 26:04.521
‐ Well, me too. Let's go do it.

26:04.521 --> 26:07.441
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:07.441 --> 26:11.695
<i>‐ I'm the last blade to test</i>
<i>and my heart's racing</i>

26:11.695 --> 26:12.696
100 miles an hour.

26:12.696 --> 26:13.072
[exhales]

26:15.866 --> 26:18.160
<i>Any little failure in my blade</i>
<i>could be sending me home</i>

26:18.160 --> 26:20.954
and lose the chance to compete
for that $50,000.

26:20.954 --> 26:24.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:24.291 --> 26:27.795
‐ [grunting]

26:27.795 --> 26:33.634
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:33.634 --> 26:36.637
[grunting]

26:36.637 --> 26:43.268
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:44.228 --> 26:46.105
Congratulations, Tyler.

26:46.105 --> 26:49.775
Your tip held up fine,
your edges are still sharp.

26:49.775 --> 26:51.235
It's all tight and good.
Good job.

26:51.235 --> 26:52.653
‐ Thank you.

26:52.653 --> 26:54.404
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:54.404 --> 26:56.365
‐ Jack, I feel terrible
about this,

26:56.365 --> 27:00.327
but the fact is is that I have
two complete V‐42s over there,

27:00.327 --> 27:02.871
and then I have one
that's missing a skull cracker.

27:02.871 --> 27:05.249
You can no longer be measured
evenly and fairly

27:05.249 --> 27:06.834
with your competitors,
and for that reason

27:06.834 --> 27:08.418
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

27:08.418 --> 27:10.087
Come on forward,
Sergeant Major.

27:10.087 --> 27:11.839
Thank you so much.
‐ Thank you, brother.

27:11.839 --> 27:14.758
The blade was perfect.
It performed phenomenally.

27:14.758 --> 27:16.552
<i>But you gotta have a handle</i>
<i>on your knife,</i>

27:16.552 --> 27:19.513
so that's the end of it.

27:19.513 --> 27:21.348
<i>I may not be the "Forged</i>
<i>in Fire" champion,</i>

27:21.348 --> 27:23.183
but I'm proud of the work
I did here.

27:23.183 --> 27:24.935
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:24.935 --> 27:26.645
I just wanna tell my fellow
competitors out there

27:26.645 --> 27:28.188
to kick ass
and bring it home for the army.

27:28.188 --> 27:31.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:31.942 --> 27:33.277
‐ Fermin, Tyler,
congratulations.

27:33.277 --> 27:34.778
You boys have made it

27:34.778 --> 27:36.530
to the final round
of this competition,

27:36.530 --> 27:38.574
which means that you're both
one step closer

27:38.574 --> 27:40.284
to representing the army

27:40.284 --> 27:42.703
in our Battle
of the Branches final.

27:42.703 --> 27:44.621
Now, we're sending you
back to your home forges

27:44.621 --> 27:47.207
to recreate this iconic weapon.

27:47.207 --> 27:49.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:49.167 --> 27:51.086
The US Army Officer Sword.

27:51.086 --> 27:54.089
‐ [gasps] Oh, snap.

27:54.089 --> 27:56.049
The saber.

27:56.049 --> 27:58.135
<i>‐ The US Army Officer Saber</i>

27:58.135 --> 28:00.470
<i>has adorned the dress uniforms</i>
<i>of the top brass</i>

28:00.470 --> 28:02.389
<i>for over a century,</i>

28:02.389 --> 28:05.225
<i>but its predecessors</i>
<i>are as old as America itself.</i>

28:05.225 --> 28:07.728
<i>Since the establishment</i>
<i>of the first Continental Army</i>

28:07.728 --> 28:11.398
<i>by the Second Continental</i>
<i>Congress in June of 1775,</i>

28:11.398 --> 28:12.941
<i>American officers have been</i>

28:12.941 --> 28:14.943
<i>carrying their swords</i>
<i>into battle.</i>

28:14.943 --> 28:17.404
<i>As firearms slowly</i>
<i>replaced swords in combat,</i>

28:17.404 --> 28:21.116
<i>the ceremonial Officer Saber</i>
<i>was unveiled in 1902.</i>

28:21.116 --> 28:22.951
<i>Though shorter</i>
<i>and more delicately curved,</i>

28:22.951 --> 28:24.995
<i>this highly decorated weapon</i>
<i>descends</i>

28:24.995 --> 28:27.623
<i>from the fierce battle</i>
<i>swords of the US Cavalry.</i>

28:27.623 --> 28:30.626
<i>Today, the Army Officer Saber</i>
<i>remains a crowd pleaser</i>

28:30.626 --> 28:33.295
<i>at military ceremonies,</i>
<i>weddings, and parades.</i>

28:33.295 --> 28:35.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:35.130 --> 28:38.133
Your final challenge is to
forge a US Army Officer Saber.

28:38.133 --> 28:40.135
It must fall within
the following parameters.

28:40.135 --> 28:43.138
The length of the blade must be
between 27 and 28 inches,

28:43.138 --> 28:44.640
<i>the depth of the curve must be</i>

28:44.640 --> 28:46.767
<i>between 1/2</i>
<i>and 3/4 of an inch,</i>

28:46.767 --> 28:49.978
<i>and your blade must include</i>
<i>a three‐bar saber guard</i>

28:49.978 --> 28:51.438
<i>and a knuckle bow.</i>

28:51.438 --> 28:53.106
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:53.106 --> 28:55.233
‐ I am super excited to get
this thing taken care of.

28:55.233 --> 28:56.902
Bring it home
for the United States Army.

28:56.902 --> 28:58.612
Hooah!

28:58.612 --> 29:01.114
‐ Gentlemen, you'll have
four days at your home

29:01.114 --> 29:02.991
forges in which
to complete this challenge.

29:02.991 --> 29:05.285
At the end of those four days,
you'll return and present

29:05.285 --> 29:07.579
your sabers
to our panel of expert judges.

29:07.579 --> 29:09.373
And after they've thoroughly
tested them, they'll move

29:09.373 --> 29:12.626
one of you forward to our
Battle of the Branches final

29:12.626 --> 29:14.586
to represent the army.

29:14.586 --> 29:16.838
Good luck bladesmiths,
we'll see you in four days.

29:16.838 --> 29:18.382
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:18.382 --> 29:19.633
‐ Thanks.
‐ Good luck, Fermin.

29:19.633 --> 29:20.926
‐ Good luck.

29:20.926 --> 29:24.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:24.346 --> 29:26.723
<i>Day one, I'm finally back</i>
<i>on my home forge.</i>

29:26.723 --> 29:29.851
<i>What I'm gonna use</i>
<i>is a 1095 high‐carbon steel.</i>

29:29.851 --> 29:31.561
<i>Making a blade this long,</i>

29:31.561 --> 29:33.397
it's gonna be a little bit
of a challenge for me.

29:33.397 --> 29:37.317
I have a two‐burner forge and
the blade is 27 inches long.

29:37.317 --> 29:39.736
<i>Adapt, improvise,</i>
<i>and overcome!</i>

29:39.736 --> 29:41.780
<i>I have an extra forge,</i>

29:41.780 --> 29:43.740
<i>so I'm gonna try to put it</i>
<i>behind the other forge</i>

29:43.740 --> 29:45.659
and see if I can
just do an entire blade.

29:45.659 --> 29:46.868
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:46.868 --> 29:48.954
Now, that's fire! [laughing]

29:48.954 --> 29:51.289
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:51.289 --> 29:53.417
<i>I have the general profile</i>
<i>of what I need.</i>

29:53.417 --> 29:54.835
But I need to get
that curve on it.

29:54.835 --> 29:56.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:56.336 --> 29:59.047
<i>I'm actually forcing</i>
<i>the blade bend,</i>

29:59.047 --> 30:02.217
so that way I can get that
arch between 1/4 of an inch

30:02.217 --> 30:03.677
and 3/4 of an inch.

30:03.677 --> 30:05.178
There it is. Perfect.

30:05.178 --> 30:09.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:09.099 --> 30:11.268
<i>‐ It's day one, I'm back in</i>
<i>my home forge</i>

30:11.268 --> 30:12.811
in Weyauwega, Wisconsin.

30:12.811 --> 30:14.646
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:14.646 --> 30:16.565
<i>So my plan is gonna be</i>
<i>to start out with a nice,</i>

30:16.565 --> 30:19.234
25‐plus layer
of billeted Damascus.

30:19.234 --> 30:20.277
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:20.277 --> 30:22.237
<i>The Damascus is a risk,</i>

30:22.237 --> 30:24.823
<i>but as long as my blade does</i>
<i>perform as I expect it to,</i>

30:24.823 --> 30:26.241
my Damascus is gonna be

30:26.241 --> 30:27.617
that thing
that puts me over the top.

30:27.617 --> 30:29.661
I've got my stack
of 1084 right here,

30:29.661 --> 30:32.205
and then I've got my stack
of 15N20 here.

30:32.205 --> 30:34.624
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:34.624 --> 30:37.044
Ready to rock and roll
and get this into the forge.

30:37.044 --> 30:39.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:39.629 --> 30:41.548
<i>I made a log splitter press,</i>

30:41.548 --> 30:45.052
so that's giving me
22 tons of squish‐squish.

30:45.052 --> 30:52.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:52.100 --> 30:54.144
Probably cut this
into about four bars,

30:54.144 --> 30:58.565
which will put us
at 108 layers, restacked.

30:58.565 --> 31:00.442
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:00.442 --> 31:02.110
Then we'll get 'em over
to the welder.

31:02.110 --> 31:04.029
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:04.029 --> 31:06.281
We're so hot in there,
it's like looking at the sun.

31:06.281 --> 31:08.325
<i>Day one's coming to a close.</i>

31:08.325 --> 31:11.495
<i>I'm just getting that last bit</i>
<i>of length out of my billet.</i>

31:11.495 --> 31:13.038
<i>Kind of looking like a saber.</i>

31:13.038 --> 31:16.041
Hup three‐‐oh, [bleep].

31:16.041 --> 31:18.668
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:18.668 --> 31:20.170
‐ We got a quench tank.

31:20.170 --> 31:21.838
I'm hoping
the quench goes well.

31:21.838 --> 31:23.548
That way,
I can move on to the guard.

31:23.548 --> 31:24.925
[laughs excitedly]

31:24.925 --> 31:27.886
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:27.886 --> 31:30.597
<i>I get that blade</i>
<i>into the oil.</i>

31:30.597 --> 31:32.099
No pings.

31:32.099 --> 31:33.558
That's a good sign.
That's a very good sign.

31:33.558 --> 31:34.726
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:34.726 --> 31:36.394
[bleep].

31:36.394 --> 31:38.396
When I pulled the blade
out of the quench,

31:38.396 --> 31:40.482
the blade actually straightened
out instead of taking a curve.

31:40.482 --> 31:42.651
<i>So now,</i>
<i>I'm under the perimeters.</i>

31:42.651 --> 31:44.152
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:44.152 --> 31:45.946
<i>I put my blade</i>
<i>back in the heat,</i>

31:45.946 --> 31:47.614
<i>I bring it out, I put it</i>
<i>on the jig that I made.</i>

31:47.614 --> 31:48.698
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:48.698 --> 31:50.033
I don't wanna overcool it,

31:50.033 --> 31:51.618
because I don't wanna break it.

31:51.618 --> 31:53.036
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:53.036 --> 31:54.329
I made it!

31:54.329 --> 31:55.413
It's time
to move on to the guard.

31:55.413 --> 31:57.541
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:57.541 --> 31:59.501
I have never made
anything like this before,

31:59.501 --> 32:01.920
<i>so this is a very</i>
<i>big challenge for me.</i>

32:01.920 --> 32:03.922
I have the metal moving
to where I want it to move.

32:03.922 --> 32:05.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:05.090 --> 32:06.341
Sweet!

32:06.341 --> 32:08.301
This is the end of day two.

32:08.301 --> 32:11.304
Got a blade, got a guard,
I'm glad it's over.

32:12.305 --> 32:13.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:13.932 --> 32:15.517
<i>‐ It's day two here</i>
<i>at my home forge.</i>

32:15.517 --> 32:17.477
It's time to quench.

32:17.477 --> 32:18.937
<i>I'm really crossing</i>
<i>my fingers here</i>

32:18.937 --> 32:21.940
<i>that everything</i>
<i>is gonna go as planned.</i>

32:21.940 --> 32:23.525
[laughs evilly]

32:23.525 --> 32:25.902
'Cause I don't
wanna have to start over.

32:25.902 --> 32:27.487
Temperature feels good.

32:27.487 --> 32:34.494
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:37.289 --> 32:40.333
We got a real, real
slight warp at the end.

32:40.333 --> 32:42.711
I think that's something
I can grind out.

32:42.711 --> 32:44.462
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:44.462 --> 32:45.839
The file skates.

32:45.839 --> 32:48.925
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:48.925 --> 32:51.011
<i>‐ Today's the last day.</i>
<i>I'm starting day four.</i>

32:51.011 --> 32:53.138
<i>I'm concentrating</i>
<i>on sharpening that blade</i>

32:53.138 --> 32:54.639
and getting the handle done.

32:54.639 --> 33:00.437
It's the G10 handle
with gold G10 spacers.

33:00.437 --> 33:02.397
<i>This handle represents</i>
<i>the Golden Knights.</i>

33:02.397 --> 33:04.649
It's a United States Army
parachute team.

33:04.649 --> 33:06.902
Looking good so far.
It's nice and tight,

33:06.902 --> 33:08.987
now to just get a drill bit
right through it.

33:08.987 --> 33:11.990
<i>[tense music]</i>

33:11.990 --> 33:17.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:17.162 --> 33:18.622
My handle snaps.

33:18.622 --> 33:21.082
Don't do this to me!

33:21.082 --> 33:22.000
Not good.

33:24.836 --> 33:27.172
‐ [You can see where the crack
just went right in it.

33:27.172 --> 33:29.549
<i>Once again, and</i>
<i>I cannot say this enough:</i>

33:29.549 --> 33:31.843
the army teaches us, when
something gets thrown at you,

33:31.843 --> 33:34.054
you have to adapt, improvise,
and overcome.

33:34.054 --> 33:36.306
<i>I wanted to keep</i>
<i>the same theme,</i>

33:36.306 --> 33:38.850
<i>so I'm gonna go with</i>
<i>Purple Heart,</i>

33:38.850 --> 33:41.144
<i>one of the highest honors</i>
<i>that you can receive</i>

33:41.144 --> 33:43.772
<i>while being in war</i>
<i>and surviving.</i>

33:43.772 --> 33:45.273
<i>Today's the last day,</i>

33:45.273 --> 33:47.234
<i>and I can't make</i>
<i>any other mistakes.</i>

33:47.234 --> 33:49.069
Let's hope it works. [laughs]

33:49.069 --> 33:53.198
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:53.198 --> 33:54.741
So now, little bit of epoxy.

33:54.741 --> 33:57.786
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:57.786 --> 34:00.121
We are successful on this one.

34:00.121 --> 34:01.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:01.748 --> 34:03.750
<i>‐ It's day four here</i>
<i>at my home forge.</i>

34:03.750 --> 34:06.169
<i>The plan for the day is</i>
<i>to finish shaping my handle,</i>

34:06.169 --> 34:08.255
<i>get everything polished up,</i>
<i>put together,</i>

34:08.255 --> 34:10.423
<i>and finishing up a blade</i>
<i>that I'm happy with.</i>

34:10.423 --> 34:11.675
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:11.675 --> 34:13.385
<i>I rounded off a piece of wood</i>

34:13.385 --> 34:15.720
to help me develop
that curve in the guard.

34:15.720 --> 34:17.055
It's a good start.

34:17.055 --> 34:19.182
We're gonna
bring out that Damascus.

34:19.182 --> 34:22.894
<i>The most rewarding part about</i>
<i>making Damascus</i>

34:22.894 --> 34:24.479
is going into the acid.

34:24.479 --> 34:27.232
I'm just 110% pleased with it.

34:27.232 --> 34:30.402
The contrast is great,
and the pattern is awesome.

34:30.402 --> 34:34.739
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:34.739 --> 34:37.367
I can't wait to see this blade
tested by the judges.

34:37.367 --> 34:41.288
Hopefully I can hear...
[as Doug] "It will kill."

34:41.288 --> 34:47.335
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:47.335 --> 34:49.212
‐ Fermin, Tyler,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:49.212 --> 34:52.382
You soldiers have had four days
at your home forges to work

34:52.382 --> 34:55.969
on your Army Officer Sabers.
Tyler, what'd you bring?

34:55.969 --> 34:57.804
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:57.804 --> 35:00.473
<i>‐ I made a 111‐layer</i>
<i>Damascus saber</i>

35:00.473 --> 35:04.144
<i>using 1084 and 15N20,</i>
<i>mild steel for the guard,</i>

35:04.144 --> 35:06.479
<i>and some African blackwood</i>
<i>for the handle.</i>

35:06.479 --> 35:08.481
‐ Nice. Fermin, how did it go?

35:08.481 --> 35:09.983
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:09.983 --> 35:11.151
<i>‐ The construction</i>
<i>of the blade</i>

35:11.151 --> 35:12.694
<i>is a 1095 high‐carbon steel.</i>

35:12.694 --> 35:14.529
<i>I went with</i>
<i>a Purple Heart handle.</i>

35:14.529 --> 35:17.490
<i>It represents the honor</i>
<i>and the valor of our soldiers.</i>

35:17.490 --> 35:19.951
‐ All right. Now it's time
for our weapons test,

35:19.951 --> 35:21.703
a strength test,
a sharpness test,

35:21.703 --> 35:23.204
and a kill test.

35:23.204 --> 35:26.166
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:26.166 --> 35:28.585
‐ [chuckles]
[both laugh]

35:28.585 --> 35:31.463
All right, soldiers,
your weapons look beautiful,

35:31.463 --> 35:33.131
but were they born to kill?

35:33.131 --> 35:35.342
To find that out,
I'm gonna take your weapons

35:35.342 --> 35:38.303
and deliver slashes and thrusts
on this ballistics dummy.

35:38.303 --> 35:40.221
Tyler, you're up first.
You ready for this?

35:40.221 --> 35:41.556
‐ Ready as I'll ever be.

35:41.556 --> 35:43.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:43.016 --> 35:45.644
There's no more gruesome
or awesome test

35:45.644 --> 35:48.271
than seeing a ballistics
dummy potentially...

35:48.271 --> 35:49.689
<i>[laughing] ...cut to pieces.</i>

35:49.689 --> 35:56.655
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:03.662 --> 36:07.624
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:07.624 --> 36:09.042
[teeth clatter]

36:09.042 --> 36:10.335
[exhales]

36:10.335 --> 36:11.503
‐ You need those teeth.

36:11.503 --> 36:12.837
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:12.837 --> 36:14.506
‐ Alas, poor Yorick,
I knew him well.

36:14.506 --> 36:18.134
[all chuckling]

36:18.134 --> 36:20.095
‐ [exhales]

36:20.095 --> 36:22.430
‐ All right, Tyler.
This edge is sharp.

36:22.430 --> 36:24.015
I mean,
just pulling out of that,

36:24.015 --> 36:26.559
look how deeply it cut
this ballistics dummy.

36:26.559 --> 36:30.271
Now, in cutting the spine
and the jaw,

36:30.271 --> 36:32.273
it took a little bit
of glinting.

36:32.273 --> 36:34.025
But no major chips,

36:34.025 --> 36:38.488
stayed straight,
and most of all, it will kill.

36:38.488 --> 36:41.741
‐ Thank you.
[all chuckling]

36:41.741 --> 36:43.618
‐ Fermin, are you ready?
‐ Sir, yes, sir.

36:43.618 --> 36:45.203
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:45.203 --> 36:46.663
<i>Watching Doug Marcaida</i>
<i>take my weapon</i>

36:46.663 --> 36:48.748
into his hands,
it is such an honor.

36:48.748 --> 36:51.543
<i>I want that Army anvil.</i>
<i>I'm ready.</i>

36:51.543 --> 36:53.545
[exhales]

36:53.545 --> 36:56.297
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:56.297 --> 36:59.092
<i>[rock music]</i>

36:59.092 --> 37:06.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:13.314 --> 37:14.941
[chuckles]

37:14.941 --> 37:16.943
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

37:16.943 --> 37:19.404
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:19.404 --> 37:21.990
As soon as I see the bend
on my blade, my heart stops.

37:21.990 --> 37:23.742
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:23.742 --> 37:27.620
‐ All right, Fermin. Your edge
will lacerate and cut flesh;

37:27.620 --> 37:29.122
your tip is sharp

37:29.122 --> 37:32.041
to puncture, from the back,
even into the heart;

37:32.041 --> 37:34.669
and it lacerates
on the way out.

37:34.669 --> 37:38.214
But, in cutting the head
and cutting that spine,

37:38.214 --> 37:40.008
it did take a bend,

37:40.008 --> 37:43.386
and there is light chipping
on the edge of your blade.

37:43.386 --> 37:46.014
But your weapon, sir,
will kill.

37:46.014 --> 37:47.640
‐ Yeah! [laughs]

37:47.640 --> 37:51.186
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:51.186 --> 37:53.813
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the strength test...

37:53.813 --> 37:55.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:55.231 --> 37:57.108
Which tests the strength
of your blade

37:57.108 --> 37:59.068
and the overall construction
of your sabers.

37:59.068 --> 38:01.946
I'm gonna beat them
violently into these helmets

38:01.946 --> 38:04.324
like they were being worn
by my mortal enemy.

38:04.324 --> 38:05.992
Now, I'm not really concerned
about what your saber

38:05.992 --> 38:07.827
does to the helmets
or the dummy.

38:07.827 --> 38:09.329
I wanna see
what the helmet and dummy

38:09.329 --> 38:11.039
are gonna do to your sabers.

38:11.039 --> 38:12.540
Now Fermin, we're gonna let
your blood pressure cool

38:12.540 --> 38:14.083
down a little bit.
‐ [laughs] Thank you.

38:14.083 --> 38:16.127
‐Tyler, you're gonna go first.
You ready?

38:16.127 --> 38:17.670
‐ Yup.
‐ Yes!

38:17.670 --> 38:19.714
[both laugh]

38:19.714 --> 38:23.218
‐ Fermin's blade takes a bend,
and mine could be next.

38:23.218 --> 38:24.719
<i>It could go anywhere.</i>

38:24.719 --> 38:25.470
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>what's gonna happen.</i>

38:29.098 --> 38:31.768
<i>[rushing music]</i>

38:31.768 --> 38:33.812
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:33.812 --> 38:36.648
‐ [grunting]

38:36.648 --> 38:43.655
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:45.490 --> 38:48.159
‐ [gasps comically]
‐ [laughing]

38:48.159 --> 38:50.245
‐ Tyler, this is a beast.

38:50.245 --> 38:51.830
You got some chipping
on the edge

38:51.830 --> 38:53.581
where I can catch my nail on.

38:53.581 --> 38:57.168
I don't see any pulls
or delaminations in your steel.

38:57.168 --> 39:00.171
Still in one piece,
and it's still sharp. Good job.

39:00.171 --> 39:01.506
‐ Thank you.
‐ Awesome, dude.

39:01.506 --> 39:03.758
‐ Thanks, man.
‐ Okay, Fermin.

39:03.758 --> 39:05.677
How you feeling?

39:05.677 --> 39:07.512
[laughter]

39:07.512 --> 39:09.055
‐ [laughing] I can't.

39:09.055 --> 39:10.390
‐ Well, we're gonna
do it anyway. [laughs]

39:10.390 --> 39:12.225
‐ [laughing] Okay.

39:12.225 --> 39:14.853
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:14.853 --> 39:17.772
My palms are sweating.
I'm almost hyperventilating.

39:17.772 --> 39:19.232
<i>I'm shaking.</i>

39:19.232 --> 39:21.985
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:21.985 --> 39:23.111
‐ [grunts]

39:23.111 --> 39:25.989
<i>[musical sting]</i>

39:25.989 --> 39:28.199
‐ Ah!

39:28.199 --> 39:29.951
[judges groan]

39:29.951 --> 39:32.996
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:32.996 --> 39:36.499
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:36.499 --> 39:38.084
All right, Fermin,
we got two problems.

39:38.084 --> 39:41.129
One, your blade
is just continuing to bend.

39:41.129 --> 39:43.756
Pretty soon, it's gonna be
a 90 degree angle.

39:43.756 --> 39:46.009
The other thing is
your handle grooves

39:46.009 --> 39:48.970
are shoving my hand
right up against the guard,

39:48.970 --> 39:51.222
and it's just bashing
my knuckles up into it.

39:51.222 --> 39:53.266
You can see my back
two knuckles

39:53.266 --> 39:55.393
are already starting
to turn blue and swell.

39:55.393 --> 39:56.853
That's a really
big problem for me.

39:56.853 --> 40:03.818
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:05.069 --> 40:07.739
‐ Gentlemen, these tests are
intentionally brutal

40:07.739 --> 40:10.408
and severe to set your blades
apart from one another.

40:10.408 --> 40:12.076
Fermin, we had
a catastrophic failure

40:12.076 --> 40:13.870
in the middle
of our strength test,

40:13.870 --> 40:17.040
and we just cannot continue
testing with that bent blade.

40:17.040 --> 40:18.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:18.666 --> 40:21.920
I have to dismiss you from
The Forge. Thank you so much.

40:21.920 --> 40:23.713
Thank you.
‐ It was an honor.

40:23.713 --> 40:24.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:24.923 --> 40:26.424
<i>I gave it my best.</i>

40:26.424 --> 40:28.134
‐ Thank you, Sergeant.
‐ I totally agree

40:28.134 --> 40:29.761
with shutting the test down.

40:29.761 --> 40:31.554
I wouldn't want to test it
myself and be injured.

40:31.554 --> 40:33.431
Represent us well.
‐ I will, brother.

40:33.431 --> 40:35.266
Bye, man.
<i>‐ Tyler,</i>

40:35.266 --> 40:37.602
coming up against you
was an honor.

40:37.602 --> 40:40.605
<i>I might not be the "Forged</i>
<i>in Fire" Champion, however,</i>

40:40.605 --> 40:44.067
making it this far,
it's been an amazing trip.

40:44.067 --> 40:47.070
I would love to do it
all over again. Go army!

40:47.070 --> 40:49.447
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:49.447 --> 40:51.824
‐ Tyler, congratulations.
You've earned

40:51.824 --> 40:53.451
<i>the army's anvil</i>
<i>in our Battle</i>

40:53.451 --> 40:55.244
<i>of the Branches</i>
<i>final competition,</i>

40:55.244 --> 40:57.121
<i>where you'll have</i>
<i>a chance to win</i>

40:57.121 --> 40:59.123
the title of "Forged in Fire"
Champion for the army

40:59.123 --> 41:02.961
and a check for $50,000.

41:02.961 --> 41:04.128
Good job, brother.
[applause]

41:04.128 --> 41:05.171
‐ Thank you.

41:05.171 --> 41:06.798
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:06.798 --> 41:09.842
Feels amazing, but this
is just the first step.

41:09.842 --> 41:13.471
<i>I still gotta go up</i>
<i>against the navy, the marines,</i>

41:13.471 --> 41:17.141
<i>and the air force to prove</i>
<i>that the army can take it all.</i>

41:17.141 --> 41:19.185
I'm Tyler Hackbarth,
I'm the army champion,

41:19.185 --> 41:20.770
and I'm coming for you guys.

41:20.770 --> 41:26.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>
